('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 1, 'multiple_choice', 'Economy', 'What federal agencies regulate cryptocurrency in the United States?', 'No federal regulation exists', 'SEC, CFTC, Treasury, and banking regulators', 'Only state agencies regulate crypto', 'Federal Reserve controls all crypto', 'SEC, CFTC, Treasury, and banking regulators', 'Multiple federal agencies have overlapping cryptocurrency jurisdiction.', 'Cryptocurrency regulation in the United States involves multiple federal agencies including the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC), Treasury Department, and banking regulators, creating a complex regulatory framework with overlapping jurisdictions.', '["cryptocurrency regulation", "SEC", "CFTC", "federal agencies"]', '[{"name": "Securities and Exchange Commission - Digital Assets", "url": "https://www.sec.gov/spotlight/cybersecurity-enforcement-actions"}, {"name": "Commodity Futures Trading Commission", "url": "https://www.cftc.gov/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Cryptocurrency Regulation", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 2, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'What constitutional authority does Congress have to regulate cryptocurrency?', 'No constitutional authority', 'Commerce Clause and power to coin money', 'Only taxation authority', 'State police powers exclusively', 'Commerce Clause and power to coin money', 'Article I provides Congress with broad economic regulatory powers.', 'Congress has constitutional authority to regulate cryptocurrency through the Commerce Clause (regulating interstate and international commerce) and the power to coin money and regulate its value, providing broad federal authority over digital currency regulation and policy.', '["Commerce Clause", "coinage power", "congressional authority"]', '[{"name": "Constitution - Article I Powers", "url": "https://constitution.congress.gov/browse/article-1/section-8/"}, {"name": "Supreme Court - Commerce Clause Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/commerce-clause/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Digital Currency Authority", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 3, 'multiple_choice', 'Economy', 'How do cryptocurrency trade wars affect international economic relations?', 'No effect on international relations', 'Create tensions over financial sovereignty and monetary policy', 'Only improve international cooperation', 'Eliminate all trade disputes', 'Create tensions over financial sovereignty and monetary policy', 'Digital currency policies affect global financial relationships.', 'Cryptocurrency trade wars create tensions over financial sovereignty as nations compete to control digital currency flows, affecting monetary policy independence, cross-border payment systems, and international economic cooperation in the digital finance ecosystem.', '["financial sovereignty", "monetary policy", "international tensions"]', '[{"name": "Bank for International Settlements", "url": "https://www.bis.org/"}, {"name": "International Monetary Fund - Digital Currencies", "url": "https://www.imf.org/en/Topics/fintech"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - International Finance", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 4, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'What role does the Federal Reserve play in cryptocurrency policy?', 'Complete control over all cryptocurrencies', 'Central bank digital currency research and monetary policy oversight', 'No role in cryptocurrency matters', 'Only enforcement of existing laws', 'Central bank digital currency research and monetary policy oversight', 'The Fed focuses on monetary policy implications and CBDC development.', 'The Federal Reserve plays important roles in cryptocurrency policy through research on central bank digital currencies (CBDCs), analysis of monetary policy implications, oversight of payment systems, and coordination with other regulators on financial stability concerns.', '["Federal Reserve", "CBDC research", "monetary policy"]', '[{"name": "Federal Reserve - Digital Currencies", "url": "https://www.federalreserve.gov/central-bank-digital-currency.htm"}, {"name": "Board of Governors - Payment Systems", "url": "https://www.federalreserve.gov/paymentsystems.htm"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Federal Reserve Role", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 5, 'multiple_choice', 'Economy', 'How do sanctions affect cryptocurrency trading?', 'Sanctions don\'t apply to cryptocurrencies', 'Treasury can prohibit crypto transactions with sanctioned entities', 'Only traditional banking is affected by sanctions', 'Cryptocurrencies automatically bypass all sanctions', 'Treasury can prohibit crypto transactions with sanctioned entities', 'Financial sanctions extend to digital currency transactions.', 'Economic sanctions affect cryptocurrency trading because the Treasury Department can prohibit crypto transactions with sanctioned individuals, entities, or countries, using blockchain analysis and regulatory enforcement to prevent circumvention of sanctions through digital currencies.', '["economic sanctions", "Treasury enforcement", "crypto compliance"]', '[{"name": "Treasury - Office of Foreign Assets Control", "url": "https://home.treasury.gov/policy-issues/office-of-foreign-assets-control-sanctions-programs-and-information"}, {"name": "Financial Crimes Enforcement Network", "url": "https://www.fincen.gov/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Sanctions and Crypto", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 6, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'What national security concerns arise from cryptocurrency trade wars?', 'No national security implications', 'Financial system stability, sanctions evasion, and illicit finance', 'Only cybersecurity concerns', 'Automatic security improvements', 'Financial system stability, sanctions evasion, and illicit finance', 'Digital currencies raise multiple security and policy concerns.', 'Cryptocurrency trade wars raise national security concerns including threats to financial system stability, potential sanctions evasion through digital currencies, illicit finance activities, cybersecurity risks, and challenges to traditional monetary policy and economic control mechanisms.', '["national security", "financial stability", "sanctions evasion"]', '[{"name": "Department of Treasury - National Security", "url": "https://home.treasury.gov/policy-issues/terrorism-and-illicit-finance"}, {"name": "Financial Stability Oversight Council", "url": "https://home.treasury.gov/policy-issues/financial-markets-financial-institutions-and-fiscal-service/fsoc"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Crypto Security", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 7, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'How do First Amendment concerns relate to cryptocurrency regulation?', 'No First Amendment issues', 'Code as speech and regulatory restrictions on crypto development', 'First Amendment only protects traditional speech', 'Cryptocurrency has no speech implications', 'Code as speech and regulatory restrictions on crypto development', 'Computer code has been recognized as a form of protected expression.', 'First Amendment concerns in cryptocurrency regulation include recognition of computer code as protected speech, potential restrictions on crypto development and publication, and balancing free expression rights with legitimate regulatory objectives for financial oversight and consumer protection.', '["code as speech", "First Amendment protection", "regulatory balance"]', '[{"name": "Electronic Frontier Foundation", "url": "https://www.eff.org/"}, {"name": "Supreme Court - Speech Protection Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/first-amendment/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Technology and Speech", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 8, 'multiple_choice', 'Economy', 'What impact do Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs) have on cryptocurrency markets?', 'No impact on crypto markets', 'Competition for digital payment adoption and regulatory implications', 'Automatic elimination of private cryptocurrencies', 'Only positive effects for all digital currencies', 'Competition for digital payment adoption and regulatory implications', 'CBDCs create both competition and regulatory considerations for private crypto.', 'Central Bank Digital Currencies impact cryptocurrency markets by creating competition for digital payment adoption, influencing regulatory approaches to private cryptocurrencies, affecting monetary policy transmission, and potentially changing the landscape of digital finance and payment systems.', '["CBDC competition", "digital payments", "monetary policy"]', '[{"name": "Federal Reserve - CBDC Research", "url": "https://www.federalreserve.gov/central-bank-digital-currency.htm"}, {"name": "Bank for International Settlements - CBDCs", "url": "https://www.bis.org/topics/central_bank_digital_currencies.htm"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - CBDC Analysis", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 9, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'How do state governments respond to federal cryptocurrency policies?', 'States have no role in crypto policy', 'States create their own regulations and sometimes conflict with federal approaches', 'Complete uniformity between state and federal policy', 'States automatically follow all federal guidelines', 'States create their own regulations and sometimes conflict with federal approaches', 'Federalism creates variation in cryptocurrency regulatory approaches.', 'State governments respond to federal cryptocurrency policies by creating their own regulations that sometimes conflict with federal approaches, establishing state-level licensing requirements, pursuing different enforcement priorities, and creating a complex federalism dynamic in crypto regulation.', '["state regulation", "federalism", "regulatory conflict"]', '[{"name": "National Association of Attorneys General", "url": "https://www.naag.org/"}, {"name": "Conference of State Bank Supervisors", "url": "https://www.csbs.org/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - State Crypto Regulation", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 10, 'multiple_choice', 'Economy', 'What enforcement challenges arise in cryptocurrency regulation?', 'No enforcement challenges exist', 'Cross-border transactions, pseudonymity, and technical complexity', 'Enforcement is completely automated', 'Only traditional enforcement methods needed', 'Cross-border transactions, pseudonymity, and technical complexity', 'Digital currencies create unique regulatory enforcement challenges.', 'Cryptocurrency regulation faces enforcement challenges including the global nature of cross-border transactions, pseudonymous blockchain transactions, technical complexity requiring specialized expertise, and the rapid pace of technological innovation outpacing regulatory frameworks.', '["enforcement challenges", "cross-border issues", "technical complexity"]', '[{"name": "Financial Crimes Enforcement Network", "url": "https://www.fincen.gov/"}, {"name": "Department of Justice - Cybercrime", "url": "https://www.justice.gov/criminal/criminal-ccips"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Crypto Enforcement", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 11, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'How do privacy rights interact with cryptocurrency regulation?', 'No privacy considerations in crypto regulation', 'Fourth Amendment protections balance with legitimate regulatory oversight', 'Complete privacy elimination in all crypto transactions', 'Unlimited government surveillance authority', 'Fourth Amendment protections balance with legitimate regulatory oversight', 'Constitutional privacy rights must be balanced with regulatory objectives.', 'Privacy rights interact with cryptocurrency regulation through Fourth Amendment protections against unreasonable searches, requiring warrants for accessing private crypto wallets and transaction data, while balancing legitimate regulatory needs for financial oversight and law enforcement.', '["Fourth Amendment", "financial privacy", "regulatory balance"]', '[{"name": "Supreme Court - Fourth Amendment Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/fourth-amendment/"}, {"name": "American Civil Liberties Union - Financial Privacy", "url": "https://www.aclu.org/issues/privacy-technology"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Privacy and Finance", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 12, 'multiple_choice', 'Economy', 'What role does international cooperation play in cryptocurrency regulation?', 'No international cooperation needed', 'Coordination on standards, enforcement, and anti-money laundering efforts', 'Complete global uniformity required', 'Only bilateral agreements matter', 'Coordination on standards, enforcement, and anti-money laundering efforts', 'Global nature of crypto requires international regulatory coordination.', 'International cooperation in cryptocurrency regulation involves coordination on technical standards, enforcement of anti-money laundering requirements, sharing of regulatory best practices, and multilateral efforts to address cross-border crypto-related crimes and sanctions evasion.', '["international cooperation", "AML coordination", "global standards"]', '[{"name": "Financial Action Task Force", "url": "https://www.fatf-gafi.org/"}, {"name": "Bank for International Settlements", "url": "https://www.bis.org/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - International Crypto Cooperation", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 13, 'multiple_choice', 'Government', 'How do cryptocurrency policies affect consumer protection?', 'No consumer protection considerations', 'Fraud prevention, disclosure requirements, and market integrity', 'Automatic consumer protection through technology', 'Only traditional consumer laws apply', 'Fraud prevention, disclosure requirements, and market integrity', 'Consumer protection requires specific approaches for digital assets.', 'Cryptocurrency policies affect consumer protection through fraud prevention measures, disclosure requirements for crypto investments, market integrity oversight, protection against manipulation, and ensuring consumers understand the risks of digital asset investments.', '["consumer protection", "fraud prevention", "market integrity"]', '[{"name": "Securities and Exchange Commission - Investor Protection", "url": "https://www.sec.gov/spotlight/cybersecurity-enforcement-actions"}, {"name": "Consumer Financial Protection Bureau", "url": "https://www.consumerfinance.gov/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Consumer Crypto Protection", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 14, 'multiple_choice', 'Economy', 'What taxation issues arise from cryptocurrency trading?', 'Cryptocurrencies are not taxable', 'Capital gains, income reporting, and compliance challenges', 'Only corporate taxes apply', 'Automatic tax exemption for all crypto', 'Capital gains, income reporting, and compliance challenges', 'Crypto taxation involves complex reporting and compliance requirements.', 'Cryptocurrency trading creates taxation issues including capital gains treatment, income reporting requirements for mining and staking, compliance challenges for tracking transactions, and IRS enforcement efforts to ensure proper tax reporting of digital asset activities.', '["cryptocurrency taxation", "capital gains", "IRS compliance"]', '[{"name": "Internal Revenue Service - Digital Assets", "url": "https://www.irs.gov/individuals/international-taxpayers/frequently-asked-questions-on-virtual-currency-transactions"}, {"name": "Treasury Department - Tax Policy", "url": "https://home.treasury.gov/policy-issues/tax-policy"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Crypto Taxation", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 15, 'multiple_choice', 'Constitutional Law', 'How do due process rights apply to cryptocurrency enforcement actions?', 'No due process rights in crypto enforcement', 'Notice, hearing rights, and appeal processes for enforcement actions', 'Automatic forfeiture without process', 'Only criminal due process applies', 'Notice, hearing rights, and appeal processes for enforcement actions', 'Constitutional due process protections apply to all government enforcement.', 'Due process rights in cryptocurrency enforcement include notice of violations, hearing rights before penalties, opportunity to contest evidence, appeals processes for regulatory decisions, and protection against arbitrary enforcement actions by government agencies.', '["due process", "enforcement rights", "administrative procedure"]', '[{"name": "Administrative Procedure Act", "url": "https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/5/part-I/chapter-5"}, {"name": "Supreme Court - Due Process Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/due-process/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Administrative Due Process", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

