('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 18, 'true_false', 'Constitutional Law', 'Congress has constitutional authority to regulate cryptocurrency under the Commerce Clause.', '', '', '', '', 'True', 'The Commerce Clause provides broad authority over interstate and international commerce.', 'True. Congress has constitutional authority to regulate cryptocurrency under the Commerce Clause, which covers interstate and international commerce, and the power to coin money and regulate its value, providing broad federal authority over digital currencies.', '["Commerce Clause", "congressional authority", "constitutional power"]', '[{"name": "Constitution - Commerce Clause", "url": "https://constitution.congress.gov/browse/article-1/section-8/"}, {"name": "Supreme Court - Commerce Clause Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/commerce-clause/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Constitutional Authority", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 19, 'true_false', 'Economy', 'Economic sanctions can be applied to cryptocurrency transactions with prohibited entities.', '', '', '', '', 'True', 'Financial sanctions extend to digital currency transactions under Treasury authority.', 'True. Economic sanctions can be applied to cryptocurrency transactions with prohibited entities. The Treasury Department has authority to prohibit crypto transactions that violate sanctions laws and can track blockchain transactions to enforce compliance.', '["economic sanctions", "crypto compliance", "Treasury authority"]', '[{"name": "Treasury - OFAC Sanctions", "url": "https://home.treasury.gov/policy-issues/office-of-foreign-assets-control-sanctions-programs-and-information"}, {"name": "Financial Crimes Enforcement Network", "url": "https://www.fincen.gov/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Sanctions and Digital Assets", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 20, 'true_false', 'Government', 'State governments have no authority to regulate cryptocurrency within their borders.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'States can regulate crypto within their jurisdiction alongside federal oversight.', 'False. State governments do have authority to regulate cryptocurrency within their borders, including licensing requirements, consumer protection measures, and enforcement actions, creating a complex federalism framework alongside federal regulation.', '["state authority", "federalism", "concurrent jurisdiction"]', '[{"name": "National Association of Attorneys General", "url": "https://www.naag.org/"}, {"name": "Conference of State Bank Supervisors", "url": "https://www.csbs.org/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - State Crypto Authority", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 21, 'true_false', 'Constitutional Law', 'Computer code used in cryptocurrency development receives no First Amendment protection.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'Computer code has been recognized as protected speech in some contexts.', 'False. Computer code used in cryptocurrency development can receive First Amendment protection as a form of speech, though this protection may be balanced against legitimate regulatory interests in financial oversight and consumer protection.', '["code as speech", "First Amendment", "protected expression"]', '[{"name": "Electronic Frontier Foundation - Code Protection", "url": "https://www.eff.org/"}, {"name": "Supreme Court - Speech Protection Cases", "url": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/first-amendment/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - Technology and Speech Rights", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

('2025-04-26-cryptocurrency-trade-war', 22, 'true_false', 'Economy', 'Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs) would eliminate all private cryptocurrencies.', '', '', '', '', 'False', 'CBDCs would compete with but not necessarily eliminate private cryptocurrencies.', 'False. Central Bank Digital Currencies would not automatically eliminate all private cryptocurrencies. CBDCs would create competition and influence the market, but private cryptocurrencies could continue to exist alongside government digital currencies.', '["CBDC impact", "private crypto coexistence", "market competition"]', '[{"name": "Federal Reserve - CBDC Research", "url": "https://www.federalreserve.gov/central-bank-digital-currency.htm"}, {"name": "Bank for International Settlements", "url": "https://www.bis.org/"}, {"name": "Congressional Research Service - CBDC Analysis", "url": "https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/R/R45427"}]'),

